Tile_X01_Y06: 14121 ms

^C^C%Error: Verilator threw signal 2. Suggest...
```

With further investigation, I noticed that the the for loop traversal count grows when processing later CGRA units:
```
        // Now for each child cell, iterate the module this cell points to
        int inner_count = 0;
        int outer_count = 0;
        std::vector<std::tuple<string, int>> inner_time;
        for (AstNode* cellnextp = nodep->stmtsp(); cellnextp; cellnextp = cellnextp->nextp()) {
            if (AstCell* const cellp = VN_CAST(cellnextp, Cell)) {

                auto t1 = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();

                VL_RESTORER(m_scopep);  // Protects m_scopep set in called module
                // which is "above" in this code, but later in code execution order
                VL_RESTORER(m_aboveCellp);
                VL_RESTORER(m_aboveScopep);
                {
                    m_aboveCellp = cellp;
                    m_aboveScopep = m_scopep;
                    AstNodeModule* const modp = cellp->modp();
                    UASSERT_OBJ(modp, cellp, "Unlinked mod");
                    iterate(modp);  // Recursive call to visit(AstNodeModule)
                    if (VN_IS(modp, Iface)) {
                        // Remember newly created scope
                        cellp->user2p(m_scopep);
                    }
                    inner_count++;
                }

                auto t2 = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();
                inner_time.push_back(std::tuple<string, int>(cellp->name(), std::chrono::duration_cast<std::chrono::milliseconds>(t2 - t1).count()));

            }
            outer_count++;
        }


        if (probe_match){
            for (auto& i : inner_time){
                if (std::get<1>(i) != 0)
                    std::cout << std::get<0>(i) << " -- " << std::get<1>(i) << std::endl; 
            }

            std::cout << "OuterCount " << outer_count << " InnerCount " << inner_count << std::endl;
            std::cout << "=================================================" << std::endl;
            timestamp_2 = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();
        }
```

To further dig it, I pick a small module "AOCell" as the ** m_aboveCellp** in the for loop above , which is simpily below:
```
module AO_CELL ( 
    input logic  A1,
    input logic  A2, 
    input logic  B1, 
    input logic  B2, 
    output logic  Z);  

    assign Z = ((A1 & A2) | (B1 & B2)); 

endmodule 
```

I then observe the for loop traversal, one can see that the number of traversal in this loop starts to get crazy with later CGRA units. The expected loop count should always be 5-6 for AOCell.

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/58b2bd11-a843-4f43-97bf-5bdfda532920)

Then I print the loop content of the AOCell, the first 5 seems reasonable, but then it meet a LinkedList Node name Null?, After that, the loop starts to traverse completely non-related other instances..

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/0f3d3ca3-55b4-4b1f-9681-c732c224f60c)

I am suspecting a bug here? When we meet a node with Name Null, do we suppose to stop the for loop here?
The following nodes in the linked list seems to be completely unrelated to this instance of AOCell.
And with later and later CGRA units, the linked list become bigger and bigger in each traverse, effectively stuck the entire ScopeAll flow.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
--------------------------------------------- Misc. ------------------------------------------
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The verilator command I use: 
```
../tools/verilator/install/bin/verilator --main --timing --cc --exe -O3 --x-assign fast -x-initial fast --output-split 10000 --output-split-cfuncs 100 -sv +1800-2017ext+sv --vpi --threads-dpi all --instr-count-dpi --trace-structs --trace-params --assert --timescale 1ns/1ns --max-num-width 1048576 --unroll-count 256 -Wall -Wno-PINCONNECTEMPTY -Wno-ASSIGNDLY -Wno-DECLFILENAME -Wno-style -Wno-BLKANDNBLK -Wno-LITENDIAN -Wno-CASEINCOMPLETE -Wno-CMPCONST -Wno-WIDTH -Wno-WIDTHCONCAT -Wno-UNSIGNED -Wno-UNOPTFLAT -Wno-fatal -Wno-UNUSED --Mdir /home/wangtianchen/Desktop/CARVIX/sims/build/workdir --top-module SimTop verilator_config.vlt -f /home/wangtianchen/Desktop/CARVIX/sims/build/files.f +define+VERILATOR +define+RESET_DELAY=777.7 +define+RANDOMIZE_MEM_INIT +define+RANDOMIZE_REG_INIT +define+RANDOMIZE_GARBAGE_ASSIGN +define+RANDOMIZE_INVALID_ASSIGN +define+PRINTF_COND=0 -fno-inline -Wno-PINMISSING -threads 6 -CFLAGS "-I/home/wangtianchen/Desktop/CARVIX/sims/build -I/home/wangtianchen/Desktop/CARVIX/sims/build/workdir -I/home/wangtianchen/Desktop/CARVIX/generators/rocket-chip/src/main/resources/csrc -I/home/wangtianchen/Desktop/CARVIX/build/rtl_codes -DVERILATOR -DTOP_TYPE=VSimTop -fcoroutines" --debug --debugi 2 --dumpi-tree 1 --gdb
```

The verilator version I use:
`Verilator 5.026 2024-06-15 rev v5.026`

What OS and distribution are you using?
`24.04.2 LTS `

**I think this only happen in the Release version of the Verilator? I am doing more investigation on it**
[Update # 1] Ok debug build also has this issue
[Update # 2] Ok, Probably it is not due to the Null in name(), but still, it is weird to see other unrelated hardware instances and modules in the iteration for loop of a AOCell.

